# Class Attribute
The class attribute in HTML is used to assign one or more class names to an element. These class names can be used by CSS and JavaScript to style or manipulate elements easily.

<tag class="class-name">Content</tag>
<p class="highlight">This is a paragraph.</p>


ğŸ“˜ Key Points
âœ… Assigns a class name to an HTML element

âœ… Can be used on any HTML element

âœ… Case-sensitive: Box and box are different

âœ… Multiple elements can share the same class

âœ… Multiple classes can be added using spaces:


ğŸ¨ Usage in CSS
.highlight {
  background-color: yellow;
  font-weight: bold;
}


Example:
<p class="highlight">Important note!</p>


âš™ï¸ Usage in JavaScript
ğŸ” Select elements by class:
const items = document.getElementsByClassName("highlight");

for (let item of items) {
  item.style.color = "red";
}


ğŸ§  Tip
You can combine id, class, and other selectors in CSS/JS for powerful styling and manipulation:

.card.primary {
  background-color: #f0f0f0;
}


ğŸ’¡ Best Practices
âœ… Use class names that are semantic and descriptive (e.g., button-primary, alert-warning)

âœ… Stick to lowercase and kebab-case (like-this) for consistency

âŒ Avoid using styling words like red-box, prefer error-message or alert


ğŸ†” HTML id Attribute Cheatsheet
The id attribute is used to assign a unique identifier to an HTML element. It is often used in CSS, JavaScript, and bookmarks to select or manipulate that exact element.

âœ… Basic Syntax
<tag id="unique-id">Content</tag>

Example:
<h1 id="main-title">Welcome to My Page</h1>


ğŸ“˜ Key Points
âœ… The id must be unique within the entire HTML document

âœ… Used by CSS and JavaScript to target a specific element

âœ… id values are case-sensitive (Header â‰  header)

âœ… An element can have only one id

âœ… Often used to create HTML bookmarks (anchor links)

âœ… JavaScript can access it using:


document.getElementById("unique-id");


ğŸ¨ Usage in CSS

#main-title {
  color: blue;
  font-size: 2rem;
}

Example:
<h1 id="main-title">Welcome!</h1>


âš™ï¸ Usage in JavaScript

const heading = document.getElementById("main-title");
heading.style.color = "red";


ğŸ”— HTML Bookmarks Example

<a href="#section2">Go to Section 2</a>

<h2 id="section2">Section 2</h2>

ğŸ”¹ Clicking the link scrolls the page to the heading with the matching id.


ğŸ’¡ Best Practices
âœ… Use meaningful and semantic names like header, footer, intro

âœ… Stick to lowercase, kebab-case (like-this) for consistency

âŒ Donâ€™t reuse the same id more than once on a page

